texts. The thread connecting all of these texts is that they each conjure up some sort of performative “stage setting,” which they invite readers to enter. By analyzing the theological function of these texts, the book sheds new light on the role of the aesthetic in Kierkegaard’s authorship, his surprising affinity for liturgy and sacrament, and his overarching effort to conjoin eros for God with this-worldly love.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aDesirexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aPerformancexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aTheaterxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aTheologyxHistoryy19th century. 4aPhilosophy & Theory. 4aReligion. 4aTheology. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / History.2bisacsh  aDerrida.  aKierkegaard.  aLevinas.  aLuther/Lutheranism.  adesire/eros.  afaith.  aliturgy.  amysticism.  aperformance.  asacrament.  atheater.  atheology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z97831111896040 cprintz978082325725640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823257287?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823257287423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823257287/original  a978-3-11-072903-0  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK